snippet.textDisplay:
I feel like the value goals might not be achievable. If someone is paying that money for a supra they want something clean,stock, never wrecked and most of all built to the build sheet. A collector isn't going to pay 6 figures for a car that's already been rebuilt(clean usa title or not this video is documentation it's been crashed and anyone who looks into the car would see this) and then had the motor pushed to the stock internal limits. It might be like resto-mods are in 10 years from now and u might be able to get closer to it then but a collector wouldnt pay top dollar for supra so far modded from factory.

Side note check the unibody rigorously. If a front impact is bad enough to push a mounting screw like a foot back and into a battery and snap a rear arm then theres alot under the surface u have to worry about.

I even had to pull over the very 1st time because my mind wasn't clicking, and it took me a couple of days for an uneasy adjusting.  I resulted just following the cars in front of me for the 1st day and being super alert on any turns I had to make. This was in a left side of the road driving country, and I guess it would have been easier if I wasn't high a lot, but that's debatable. It has nothing to do with where you are seated and everything to do with what side  of the road you are used to. IMO Swapping it is pointless if all you are going for is aesthetics.
